'''''Young Jedi Knights: Diversity Alliance''''' is a [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]] young-adult novel written by [[Kevin J. Anderson]] and [[Rebecca Moesta]]. It is the eighth volume of the ''[[Star Wars: Young Jedi Knights]]'' series, and it was first published by [[Berkley Boulevard]] in [[April]] [[1997]]. The novel was reprinted in ''[[Young Jedi Knights: The Fall of the Diversity Alliance]]'' ([[1998]]).

==Publisher's summary==
''Everyone is searching for Bornan Thul. Not only is he father to one of Jacen's and Jaina's fellow students, he holds the key to a secret coalition gaining power in the New Republic. The young Jedi Knights race across the galaxy to find him&mdash;but they may be too late. For their true enemy is about to show its treacherous face. And it will be shockingly familiar&hellip;''

==Plot summary==
Concerned for [[Raynar Thul|Raynar's]] safety in the face of his [[Parent/Legends|father's]] kidnapping, his mother, [[Aryn Dro Thul|Aryn]], requests that he return to the [[House of Thul|family]] [[Flagship/Legends|flagship]], the ''[[Tradewyn]]''. Her plan backfires when a treacherous crewmember attempts to kidnap Raynar. Raynar's fellow [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] students defend him. They then set off for [[Kuar]], the last known destination of [[Bornan Thul]]. 

Following his own leads regarding Bornan Thul's disappearance brings [[Zekk]] to [[Gammalin]], where he is shocked to discover that the world's populace has been wiped out by a [[Emperor's Plague|plague]]. Zekk encounters [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]], who considers Zekk an honorable rival. The two work together and discover that the plague was introduced by command of [[Nolaa Tarkona]], leader of the [[Diversity Alliance]]. Only Bornan Thul knows how to stop the deadly contagion that targets [[Human/Legends|humans]]. 

On Kuar, the Jedi find [[Raabakyysh|Raaba]], a [[Wookiee/Legends|Wookiee]] and friend of [[Lowbacca|Lowbacca's]] from [[Kashyyyk/Legends|Kashyyyk]]. She has joined the Diversity Alliance and invites Lowie to do so as well. The group finds [[Tyko Thul]], Raynar's uncle and Bornan's brother, who is hunted by the [[IG-88 assassin droid/Legends|assassin droid IG-88]]. The droid kidnaps Tyko, leaving the Jedi no further avenues but to return to the academy.

==Continuity==
{{Quote|Tell me, Boba Fett: under that helmet, and behind your voice synthesizer, are you perhaps&hellip;a female yourself?''"<br />"''I remove my helmet for no one.|Nolaa Tarkona and "Boba Fett," in ''Young Jedi Knights: Diversity Alliance''|<ref name="Young Jedi Knights: Diversity Alliance">''[[Young Jedi Knights: Diversity Alliance]]''</ref>}}
In [[2005]], [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett's]] appearances in ''[[Star Wars: Young Jedi Knights]]'' were [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] to be those of [[Ailyn Vel]], Fett's daughter who masqueraded as him. The retcon was first established the [[Star Wars Insider 80|''Star Wars Insider'' 80]] article "[[The History of the Mandalorians: Exploring the Evolution of a Mighty Race of Warriors|The History of the Mandalorians]]," by [[Abel G. Peña]],<ref name="Insider 80">{{InsiderCite|80|The History of the Mandalorians: Exploring the Evolution of a Mighty Race of Warriors}}</ref> and it came in part from a line in ''Young Jedi Knights: Diversity Alliance'', in which the character [[Nolaa Tarkona]] suggests that Fett could be [[Gender/Legends|female]].<ref name="Blog">{{Blog|abelgpena|15|The Anatomy of a Retcon 2: or, "Boba Fett? Where?"}}</ref>

